2 HOUSE BILL 494
1 Article – Insurance
2 11–603.
3 (c) (1) Any applicable premium rate or premium rate change of a carrier
4 subject to this subtitle shall be filed with the Commissioner:
5 (i) for insurers, in accordance with § 12–203 of this article and
6 regulations adopted under Title 31, Subtitle 10 of the Code of Maryland Regulations;
7 (ii) for nonprofit health service plans, in accordance with § 14–126 of
8 this article; and
9 (iii) for health maintenance organizations, in accordance with §
10 19–713 of the Health – General Article and regulations adopted under Title 31, Subtitle 12
11 of the Code of Maryland Regulations.
12 (2) (i) The Commissioner shall disapprove or modify a proposed
13 premium rate filing if the proposed premium rates appear, based on statistical analysis and
14 reasonable assumptions, to be inadequate, unfairly discriminatory, or excessive in relation
15 to benefits.
16 (ii) In determining whether to disapprove or modify a premium rate
17 filing of a carrier, the Commissioner shall consider, to the extent appropriate:
18 1. past and prospective loss experience in and outside the
19 State;
20 2. underwriting practice and judgment;
21 3. a reasonable margin for reserve needs;
22 4. past and prospective expenses, both countrywide and
23 those specifically applicable to the State; and
24 5. any other relevant factors in and outside the State.
25 (3) WHEN FILING A PREMIUM RATE OR PREMIUM RATE CHANGE WITH
26 THE COMMISSIONER UNDER THIS SUBSECTION, A CARRIER SHALL SUBMIT A
27 DESCRIPTION OF THE CARRIER’S PROGRESS IN MEETING THE ANNUAL PRIMARY
28 CARE INVESTMENT TARGETS ESTABLISHED BY THE STATE AS REQUIRED UNDER §
29 15–717 OF THIS ARTICLE.
30 [(3)] (4) (i) Each premium rate filing and any supporting information
31 filed under this subtitle shall be open to public inspection as soon as filed.

HOUSE BILL 494 3
1 (ii) A carrier may request a finding by the Commissioner that certain
2 information filed with the Commissioner be considered confidential commercial
3 information under § 4–335 of the General Provisions Article and not subject to public
4 inspection.
5 (iii) On request and payment of a reasonable fee, a person may obtain
6 copies of a premium rate filing and any supporting information.
7 15–717.
8 (A) THIS SECTION APPLIES TO INDIVIDUAL, GROUP, OR BLANKET HEALTH
9 INSURANCE POLICIES AND CONTRACTS DELIVERED OR ISSUED FOR DELIVERY IN
10 THE STATE BY INSURERS, NONPROFIT HEALTH SERVICE PLANS, AND HEALTH
11 MAINTENANCE ORGANIZATIONS.
12 (B) AN ENTITY SUBJECT TO THIS SECTION SHALL PROVIDE
13 REIMBURSEMENT TO HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS IN A MANNER THAT MEETS THE
14 ANNUAL PRIMARY CARE INVESTMENT TARGETS ESTABLISHED BY THE STATE ON OR
15 AFTER FEBRUARY 1, 2026.
16 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
17 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
